How the classical revival affected letters in general, theology and philosophy, is well known. Everywhere men became aware more or less distinctly that there was a new world os knowledge within their reach, but concealed from them by a mass of com- mentary and compilation, barbarous in language, and corrupt in substance, though professedly founded on the works os those great authors who were little more than names to the mediaeval scholars.
